Contrary to recent opinion, the German word Schweinhund was not invented for American World War 2 films.  The word is defined in various dictionaries thus:  
(1) (1883) Thieme-Preusser Dictionary of the English and German Languages-"Schweinhund, Swine-herd's dog; fig. vulg. filthy person";  
(2)(1888) Cassell's German-English and English-German Dictionary-"Schweinhund, Swine-herd's dog; dirty wretch"; 
(3)(1909) Cassell's New German-English, English German Dictionary-"Schweinehund, swineherd's dog; filthy fellow (vulg.)", and "Schweinhund-see Schweinehund";
(4) (1910)Muret-Sanders Encyclopaedic English-German and German-English Dictionary-"Schweinehund=Schweinhund:  Filthy (or nasty) fellow";
(5) (1941 2nd Ed) (1951 9th Ed.) Cassell's German and English Dictionary-"Schweinhund, Swineherd's dog; (vulg.) filthy fellow", and "Schweinehund, (vulg)filthy fellow";
(6) (1961) Brockhaus Illustrated Dictionary-"Schweinehund,(vulg.; cont.) scoundrel, swine; der innere Schweinehund, ones baser self";
(7) (1968 12th Ed.) Cassell's German and English Dictionary-"Schweinhund (see Schweinehund), Schwein(e)hund, scoundrel, blackgaurd, rapscallion, reprobate, (sl.) bad egg, cur, skunk, son of a gun; der innere -ehund, cowardice, faint-heartedness, funk.";
(8) (1981 1st Ed.) Collins German English Dictionary-"Schweinehund, (sl.) bastard, swine (sl), den inneren Schweinehund ueberwinden (inf) to conquer one's weaker self"
(9) (1999 4th Ed.) The New Collins German Dictionary-"-"Schweinehund, (sl.) bastard, swine (sl), den inneren Schweinehund ueberwinden (inf) to conquer one's weaker self"
PWS 9th Sept. 2006